	<p>
		Turtl notes use Markdown, a format that's easy to read and write
		and doesn't require a clunky editor.
	</p>

	<ul>
		<li>
			<div># One hash makes a large title</div>
			<div><h1>One hash makes a large title</h1></div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>## Two hashes for a smaller header</div>
			<div><h2>Two hashes for a smaller header</h2></div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>- dashes<br>- make<br>- bullets</div>
			<div><ul><li>dashes</li><li>make</li><li>bullets</li></ul></div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>1. you can make<br>1. numbered bullets<br>1. as well</div>
			<div><ol><li>you can make</li><li>numbered bullets</li><li>as well</li></ol></div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>[Making links](https://turtl.it) is easy!</div>
			<div><a target="_blank" href="https://turtl.it/">Making links</a> is easy!</div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>You can also make text __bold__ or *italic*.</div>
			<div>You can also make text <strong>bold</strong> or <em>italic</em>.</div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>Here's an image:<br>![](https://turtl.it/images<space> </space>/favicon.png)</div>
			<div>Here's an image: <img src="https://turtl.it/images/favicon.png" alt=""></div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>&gt; Quote text with a caret</div>
			<div><blockquote>Quote text with a caret</blockquote></div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>
				{{! &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;indent_code_4_spaces() {}<br><br> }}
				```<br>
				surround(<space> </space>code.by(<space> </space>'three backticks'<space> </space>));<br>
				```
			</div>
			<div>
				{{! <pre><code>indent_code_4_spaces() {}</code></pre> }}
				<pre><code>surround(code.by('three backticks'));</code></pre>
			</div>
		</li>
		<li>
			<div>
				Use backticks for `inline_code()`
			</div>
			<div>
				Use backticks for <code>inline_code()</code>
			</div>
		</li>
	</ul>

